2025-07-20

Crypto Weekly Intelligence Brief

President Donald Trump has made it clear: he wants Powell out and replaced with a loyal, ultra-dovish successor who will aggressively slash rates to ease government debt costs.

Macro Insight

Trump’s Fed Takeover Plot: A New Era for Monetary Policy

Trump has intensified his public campaign against Jerome Powell, branding him “a numbskull” and “a total and complete moron” while blaming him for costing the US “a fortune” in interest payments. While Powell’s term runs until May 2026, reports indicate Trump might preemptively announce his successor as early as September this year, effectively introducing a “shadow Fed Chair” that markets would begin to price in ahead of formal appointment.

Sources suggest Kevin Hassett, a MAGA-aligned economist and Director of the National Economic Council, is the front-runner. Hassett has openly supported dovish, ultra-loose monetary policy and hardline fiscal positions. Other contenders like Kevin Warsh and Fed Governor Christopher Waller remain on the shortlist, but Trump’s preference leans toward loyalty and policy alignment rather than technocratic expertise.

The Genius Act & 401k Crypto Exposure

In parallel, Trump is pushing to broaden crypto adoption via policy:

  • The Genius Act, signed this week, seeks to deregulate certain innovative tech sectors, indirectly benefiting the crypto and AI industries.

  • Trump is also expected to sign an executive order allowing 401k retirement plans to invest in crypto assets, unlocking a multi-trillion dollar US retirement fund sector for crypto exposure. This could be a structural tailwind for long-term crypto market capitalization.

Ultimately, markets are waking up to a potential Fed regime shift, but we believe the consensus underestimates the scale and speed of this transition under a potential Trump administration. For crypto, this is a double tailwind: lower rates plus structural inflows from retirement accounts.

Crypto Market Conditions

Bitcoin and the broader crypto market continue to move in lockstep with global liquidity trends, reaffirming the view that liquidity—not just speculation—is the primary driver of price action.

Liquidity Expansion and Bitcoin Sensitivity

Bravos Research recently highlighted the tight correlation between Bitcoin price surges and global M2 money supply growth. Their data shows that a 10% increase in global M2 has historically translated to a 90% rise in Bitcoin’s price, underlining BTC’s role as a high-beta liquidity proxy. This relationship is further validated by a 2019 Journal of Risk and Financial Management study, which emphasized crypto’s sensitivity to liquidity shocks.

Source: https://x.com/bravosresearch/status/1946240154668249306

Moreover, since 2017, the expansion of global liquidity has consistently aligned with Bitcoin rallies—most notably during the 2020-2021 bull run, when M2 growth across major central banks like the Fed and ECB surged 25%, per IMF data. Today’s renewed expansion in liquidity could be laying the groundwork for another significant uptrend.

Importantly, this challenges the mainstream narrative of Bitcoin as merely speculative. According to https://x.com/LynAldenContact’s 2024 research, Bitcoin maintains a 0.51 correlation to global M2 on a 12-month basis, suggesting that BTC is better understood as a barometer of global monetary conditions—a perspective still underappreciated by traditional finance.

On-Chain Indicators Flash Overbought

While liquidity is undeniably bullish, several key on-chain metrics are flashing short-term overbought signals, raising the likelihood of either a local correction or a period of consolidation.

  • Short-Term Holder (STH) SOPR: Currently trending above 1, this indicator signals that short-term holders are realizing profits. Repeated spikes near the 1.2-1.3 range—levels that preceded past local tops in 2021—suggest that excessive profit-taking could soon weigh on price momentum.

Source: https://charts.checkonchain.com/btconchain/realised/sthsopr_indicator/sthsopr_indicator_dark.html

  • STH MVRV Bollinger Bands: The metric is approaching the upper red band, historically associated with overbought conditions. This suggests that the market value of short-term holder coins is stretched relative to their cost basis, often a prelude to corrections.

Source: https://charts.checkonchain.com/btconchain/unrealised/sthmvrv_bollingerbands/sthmvrv_bollingerbands_dark.html

  • STH Supply in Profit/Loss Ratio: This ratio has sharply risen, with the supply in profit nearing historical highs (~100k BTC). Similar spikes have often led to profit-taking waves, increasing the risk of pullbacks.

Source: https://charts.checkonchain.com/btconchain/unrealised/supply_profitloss_ratio_sth/supply_profitloss_ratio_sth_dark.html

  • Bitcoin Perpetual Futures Funding Rates: Funding rates remain elevated and positive, indicative of aggressive long positioning. With rates peaking around 0.1%-0.2%, the market is showing signs of over-leverage, reminiscent of late-stage rallies in 2021. If funding costs remain high, it could trigger long liquidations and short-term reversals.

Source: https://charts.checkonchain.com/btconchain/derivatives/derivatives_futures_fundingrate/derivatives_futures_fundingrate_dark.html

Although, liquidity remains the ultimate tailwind for Bitcoin and altcoins, particularly with fiscal and monetary conditions globally turning stimulative. However, the short-term market structure is stretched, and historical patterns suggest caution.

Altcoin Signal Layer Update

Our latest SigmaSync Strength readings reveal important shifts in the market, which we illustrate in the accompanying chart provided in this report.

Key Observations

  • BTC vs. Gold Divergence: As of July 19, both BTC and Gold registered negative momentum, but Gold’s decline is steeper, signaling a decoupling between the two. This suggests risk markets are still cautiously optimistic, favoring crypto over traditional hedges like gold.

  • Altcoin Resilience & Decoupling: Despite BTC’s slight momentum pullback, altcoins like ETH, BNB, and SOL closed the period with positive strength readings, indicating they are gaining traction independently of Bitcoin. This kind of decoupling is characteristic of early-stage “altseason” dynamics, an idea discussed in our previous reports.

  • Volatility Highlight – CRV: The sharp move in CRV, spiking to 2.63 on July 16 before dropping back to 0.91, underscores the high volatility and event-driven nature of certain altcoins. Non-technical investors should approach such assets with caution.

The latest SigmaSync Strength data points to a market phase where altcoins are regaining momentum while BTC and Gold lose ground—potentially setting the stage for continued altcoin outperformance. However, market conditions can shift rapidly, so diversification and risk awareness remain essential.

Market Thesis – July 20, 2025 Edition

Heading into next week, the market landscape is shaped by liquidity dynamics, political regime risk in the US, and a potential shift in crypto market leadership from Bitcoin to altcoins.

On the macro front, Trump’s escalating pressure to replace Fed Chair Powell with a dovish, pro-liquidity successor is setting the stage for a structural shift in US monetary policy. While markets aren’t fully pricing this yet, the implications are clear: lower rates, weaker USD, and stronger risk assets, including crypto. Additionally, policy proposals like 401k access to crypto and the Genius Act could unlock long-term structural inflows into digital assets.

In the crypto space, the liquidity tailwind remains intact, but short-term on-chain indicators (like SOPR, MVRV Bollinger Bands, and Funding Rates) suggest that Bitcoin is overbought and vulnerable to either a local pullback or sideways consolidation.

Meanwhile, our SigmaSync Strength readings confirm growing momentum in altcoins like ETH, SOL, and BNB, even as BTC’s strength stalls. The decoupling of altcoins from BTC, alongside the weakness in Gold, could signal the early phases of an altseason rotation—but with volatility still high, caution is warranted.

Conclusion

While altcoins are showing signs of independent strength, experience tells us that sustained altcoin rallies rarely persist if Bitcoin begins to pull back sharply. With BTC still carrying significant market dominance, any meaningful correction or prolonged consolidation in BTC is likely to weigh even heavier on altcoins, potentially erasing recent gains.

Moreover, with BTC dominance still elevated (above 50%), the market structure continues to be Bitcoin-led. As such, while we observe pockets of altcoin momentum, these are still fragile and dependent on Bitcoin’s stability.

The macro liquidity backdrop remains supportive, but market timing and positioning remain critical in the near term. Stay flexible, patient, and data-driven.
